flowRoot.flowPara: Each image is displayed in the main Photos window.

Simultaneously opening multiple images at the same time is treated in the same way, except that browse buttons allow navigating through the set, and an extra button in shown to add them to the app all at once.

Open in new window displays the image in an additional secondary Photos window. This is a child of the primary Photos window, and closes along with the primary. When an image was opened from Files and is opened in a secondary window, the primary window reverts to its default state, showing the photo grid.
Add to Photos moves/copies the file to ~/Pictures and enables the edit/star button.

When an image is part of a multiple selection and is opened in a second window, it is removed from the selection. When the last image is opened in a secondary window, the primary window reverts to its default state, to show the photo grid.
TODO: is there a way to better indicate that the image is part of a set that can be browsed? Could show a prominent counter ("1/3") or even small thumbnails somewhere. This deserves investigation.
When a subsequent image is opened, it replaces the previous in the Photos window.
